name: Carlton Houston
bio: Celebrating 100th anniversary - Juanita Coleman Hospital. Former journalist, family historian MS, LA, TX, AL & Houston's Third Ward. #blackhistory

social_posts.post_text: I went through a ton of newspaper archives to figure this one out. My grandmother was the head nurse at a Black hospital in Alabama named after its founder, Juanita Coleman, 100 years ago. The things we never knew. #blackhistory

Part 2: A 100 year old mystery solved. The Juanita Coleman Hospital is an amazing story of a Black woman who founded a hospital during Jim Crow, in Demopolis, Alabama. She triumphed over major obstacles to provide health care for Black folks who were turned away from White hospitals. My grandmother was a nurse in Demopolis in the 1920s and we recently found a postcard that confirmed it. Keep digging through your old scrapbooks!! You never know what you might find...on the back of those photos. Stay tuned! There is more to this story!! #blackhistory

I love comparing old photos with Google maps and street view. Last night, I was having some fun with this cute pic of my mom growing up in Houston, Tx. She informed me that the house in the background was home to one of her neighbors and one of our American heroes who toppled discrimination at the University of Texas in 1950. This is why I'm obsessed with the Third Ward of Houston, Texas. It's a special place. #blackhistory

My mother @evelyntxmo tells a great story about a family friend who left her mark on Texas and higher education. Dr. Artemisia Bowden led St. Phillips College @gospc in San Antonio, Texas, for more than half a century. Like my grandparents, Dr. Bowden was a civic leader.  I would give anything to listen to those conversations in my grandparent's living room.
null

This was another jackpot moment when we discovered a long-lost God child of my grandfather, Dr. William M. Drake. I'm so thankful my mother took detailed notes of their only conversation because I use them today in my family research. Mabel Kilpatrick was an educator and civic leader like my grandfather. They both fought for racial equality. @pvamu naacp_hou #blackhistory

It has taken years of research to begin to understand my grandfather's life.  Dr. William Marcellus Drake was a gifted surgeon with an incredible drive to overcome obstacles. He was a pioneer in women's health, traveling the country, performing major surgeries to improve lives. He was a graduate of @meharrymedicalcollege, and I feel like he's finally telling his own story. #blackhistory #womenshealth #blackwomenshealth

Latest discovery: my grandfather... laughing. It was captured during a group photo shoot 82 years ago at Prairie View A&M during a medical conference. This is an important reminder that even as our ancestors fought serious battles for equality before the Civil Rights era, they were whole people, with families, hopes and dreams, and a sense of humor❤️ #blackhistory @pvamu
Back in the day😄 Webster Groves, Mo (St. Louis)

Amazing discovery - I stumbled on this one, digging through newspaper archives about my grandfather, Dr. William M. Drake. He was always busy as a surgeon and community activist before the Civil Rights era began. I thank my grandmother, Inez Taylor Drake, who took many of these photos. She captured his legacy and has given us so many clues to understand where I come from. #blackhistory

May the best marching band win! Celebrating the annual #bayouclassic game between @southernu_br and @grambling1901 This is my mother @evelyntxmo and some throwback pics when she had her eye on a certain Alpha man strutting about campus❤️

My grandparents were always thinking about the future of their children in Baton Rouge, Louisiana. After my grandmother died, my Dad discovered his name was on the deed of his childhood home. It was a total surprise. He shared this story with us almost 30 years ago. He basically told me, "You'll appreciate this when you are older." He was right.

This was a major family history discovery that ultimately led to more questions about my grandfather Dr. William M. Drake and his connection to Booker T. Washington. This was one of our first clues that my grandfather's leadership and activism extended beyond medicine. We found this information 20 years ago. We're still searching for more answers. #blackhistory #bookertwashington

This week, I'm honoring the 100th anniversary of my grandfather's arrival in Houston, Texas. This was a new beginning for Dr. William M. Drake.  He would make his mark on the front lines of medicine and the fight for justice before the Civil Rights era. He and my grandmother would raise a family in Houston and perform surgeries together at the Houston Negro Hospital later known as Riverside General. #blackhistory

Super excited to share with you the full story of the Juanita Coleman Hospital. It's an amazing story of courage against all odds... 100 years ago, Coleman opened a hospital in her own name in Demopolis, Alabama. Her sacrifice and accomplishments were lost in the history books for decades. Now her story is finally being told. Link in my bio #blackhistory #tuskegee #bookertwashington
Answer: Hog Maws... Baton Rouge.
Celebrating the legacy of Juanita Coleman, a trailblazer in medicine! Read her story: the link is in my bio. Watch this video for insight on how it all came together.

Here's a fun discovery I recently made. It was totally random. My grandfather rode horses and he drove automobiles. I often wondered about his first "machine" as they called them. I NEVER imagined I would EVER find the answer. Sometimes, I think my grandfather is leading me on this journey. 😊 #blackhistory

It's truly amazing what you can find online these days. It is making family research so much more accessible. The other night, I discovered new photos and information about my mother's half-sister who graduated from Howard University nearly a century ago (shout out to her AKA sisters). Start searching yearbooks online... so much history! #blackhistory

This is one of my treasures. My mother, @evelyntxmo, pulled together a book of family recipes that go back more than a century. It's a snapshot into our history, the food my people grew and raised in Antioch Colony - a freedom colony near Austin, Texas. They didn't have everything, but they made it work. Sallie Kavanagh Taylor was my great-grandmother. I hope you take time to save those recipes and enjoy the holidays!

#soulfood #blackhistory @isawstephen

I found a great book that explains in part how our family ended up in Webster Groves, Missouri, which is outside of St. Louis. This is why it's important to study history. Many American families experienced what my parents went through in the 1960s to find a safe neighborhood to raise their family. #blackhistory #webstergroves #stlouis

Crazy and amazing end to 2023! I found this detailed history of one of the first schools for Blacks in Hempstead, Texas. My grandfather was the principal there 120 years ago. This is one of the earliest photos of the school, which gave Black families a chance at improving their lives by educating the children. It's the first time we've ever seen a photograph of our grandfather, Prof William Drake, at the school. This was 10 years before he became a surgeon. The document is online at Prairie View Digital Commons library. 🙌🏿#blackhistory #texashistory

Here's the short answer to a question I hear a lot. My journey to learn about my ancestors started by saving copies of everything. My mother would write stories and make copies of letters and photos. I would collect them in a notebook. Over the years, the books and photos made me ask questions. I am, by nature, a curious person. The answers continue to tell our story. #blackhistory #genealogist #familyhistory

I believe we grow into our family history. As we get older, the past becomes more meaningful. We start to ask questions that we didn't think of when we were younger.  This is a perfect example. My mother compiled her love story with my dad. After years of just flipping the pages, I finally started to read it slowly. It is revealing and heartwarming, teaching me things I never knew! Thank you Ma❤️ @evelyntxmo
#blackhistory #thirdwardhouston #weddingdress

Listen carefully to the stories of your ancestors. I truly believe the smallest details can actually help us understand our past. My grandparents owned a family grocery store.  It took many years for me to understand that the store represented more than just a way to earn money. It kept the family safe and close to home during difficult times in our history. #blackhistory #batonrouge #Louisiana
